[[File:Karolinska Institutet Science Park.JPG|thumb|Science for Life Laboratory at [[Karolinska Institutet]] Campus Solna]]
'''SciLifeLab''' (Science for Life Laboratory) is a world leading Swedish national center for large-scale research<ref>{{cite web|url=http://suls.se/project/science-for-life-laboratory-%E2%80%93-scilifelab/|date=28 November 2014|title=Science for Life Laboratory|accessdate=28 November 2014|website=Suls.se|publisher=suls.se|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204123654/http://suls.se/project/science-for-life-laboratory-%E2%80%93-scilifelab/|archivedate=4 December 2014|df=}}</ref> and one of the largest molecular biology research laboratories in Europe at the forefront of innovation in life sciences research, [[computational biology]], bioinformatics, training and services in molecular biosciences with focus on health and environmental research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/site/feature/data/prizes/scilifelab/index.xhtml|date=28 November 2014|title=Science journal|accessdate=28 November 2014|website=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|publisher=Science}}</ref> The center combines frontline technical expertise with advanced knowledge of translational medicine and molecular bioscience. SciLifeLab is a joint effort between four of the best ranked institutions in Sweden and Scandinavia ([[Karolinska Institutet]]—the institution that awards the [[Nobel Prize in Physiology or Medicine]], [[KTH Royal Institute of Technology]], [[Stockholm University]] and [[Uppsala University]]). The National Genomics Infrastructure (NGI) hosted at SciLifeLab offers large-scale DNA sequence data generation and analysis.
SciLifeLab was established in 2010 and was appointed a national center in 2013 by the Swedish government. More than 200 elite research groups composed by 1,500 researchers<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.scilifelab.se/fellows/|date=28 November 2014|accessdate=28 November 2014|title=SciLifeLab Fellow|website=[[SciLifeLab Fellows]]|publisher=ki.se}}</ref> are associated and work at SciLifeLab's two campuses in Stockholm and Uppsala. The Stockholm campus is surrounded by one of the largest hospitals in Europe both the old and the new [[Karolinska University Hospital]] buildings, the [[Karolinska Institutet]] and the [[European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control]]. SciLifeLab is provided with SEK 150 million per year in state funds separate from other national and European grants and infrastructure support in the fields of drug discovery, drug development and fundamental research.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://ki.se/en/research/molecular-biosciences-scilifelab|date=28 November 2014|title=KISciLifeLab|accessdate=28 November 2014|website=[[Karolinska Institutet]]|publisher=ki.se}}</ref> Together with the prestigious American journal ''[[Science (journal)|Science]]'', SciLifeLab awards a young researcher prize.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/site/feature/data/prizes/scilifelab/index.xhtml|date=28 November 2014|title=Science journal|accessdate=28 November 2014|website=[[Science (journal)|Science]]|publisher=Science}}</ref> From 2018, SciLifeLab nominates [[Fritiof Sjöstrand|Sjöstrand]] Lecturer in Structural Biology that would particularly spend time with students and postdocs during a visit to Sweden <ref>https://www.scilifelab.se/events/inaugural-sjostrand-lecture-in-structural-biology-by-venki-ramakrishnan/</ref> ==External links== * [http://www.scilifelab.se/ SciLifeLab] web site * [http://www.kth.se/ KTH] web site * [http://www.ki.se/ Karolinska Institutet] web site * [http://www.su.se/ Stockholm University] web site * [http://www.uu.se/ Uppsala University] web site
